			<h3 ><a href="#p160627">Re: To (probably) discuss a lot of basics</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="http://thejapanesepage.com/forum/viewtopic.php?p=160627&amp;sid=ccca31e45dd7a790da195e88f9dcfb63#p160627"><img src="http://thejapanesepage.com/phpbb/styles/tjp-embed/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="http://thejapanesepage.com/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=25932&amp;sid=ccca31e45dd7a790da195e88f9dcfb63">Hyperworm</a></strong> &raquo; Mon 11.09.2009 9:48 am </p>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote><div><cite>ã´ã§ã³ãªã¡ã« wrote:</cite>The example given: ãç§ã¯ãããã¯å¥½ãã§ã<span style="font-weight: bold">ã</span>ãã¿ããã¯å«ãã§ããã<br />&quot;I&quot; is the subject of the following discussion. Apples? Prefer, yes. <span style="font-weight: bold">Subject particle</span>, marking that this is only part of a further sentence, thereby also serving as a way to indicate some contrast. Mandarin oranges? Heavy dislike.</div></blockquote>I don't think ã here is the subject particle - it's only the subject particle when it follows a noun. Here it just means &quot;but&quot; and has no connection to the ã that marks the subject, or at least it's easiest for me to think of it that way (I'm not sure about the true linguistic nature of connective ã).<br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>ã´ã§ã³ãªã¡ã« wrote:</cite>I don't know enough, really, to come up with another example, yet, but I think it works a little bit like this:<br /><br />I, the topic of general conversation, at this point, would like to mention apples, and when that's the case, there is liking; and our subject, really, is this person who likes apples and where mandarin oranges are the case, there is a very certain dislike that exists.<br /><br />Am I making sense?</div></blockquote>I think you've made it overly verbose and haven't really nailed down the sense of contrast that comes from using ã¯ in the first place. What if it wasn't there? What if it was a ã instead? Those are the questions you need to be able to answer. Let me show you what I think:<br /><br />ãç§<span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: red">ã¯</span></span>ããã<span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: blue">ã¯</span></span>å¥½ãã§ãããã¿ãã<span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: green">ã¯</span></span>å«ãã§ããã<br /><span style="color: red"><span style="font-weight: bold">As for me</span></span>, <span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: blue">when it comes to apples</span></span>, &lt;I&gt; <span style="font-style: italic">like</span> &lt;those&gt;, but <span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: green">when it comes to mandarins</span></span>, &lt;I&gt; <span style="font-style: italic">hate</span> &lt;those&gt;.<br />(or, <span style="color: red"><span style="font-weight: bold">Personally speaking</span></span>, I <span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: blue">do</span></span> like apples, but I <span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: green">really don't</span></span> like mandarins.)<br />ã¯ adds a little bit of build-up/suspense/emphasis on what follows it. ã's emphasis is on the noun it marks (before it).<br /><br />It's probably not necessary to have &quot;personally speaking&quot;(=ç§ã¯) in the above; contrasting yourself with other people isn't the point of the sentence. The fact that you're the topic will be inferred without ç§ã¯. It doesn't do much harm being there, though; &quot;personally speaking&quot; seems like it could stand in most contexts.<br />However, ãããã¯ will only work if you're planning to contrast the ããã. If you say<br /><br />ãç§<span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: red">ã¯</span></span>ããã<span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: blue">ã¯</span></span>å¥½ãã§ãããã¹ãã¹ãã<span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: green">ã¯</span></span>ãã¾ãå¥½ãã§ã¯ããã¾ããã<br />it will mean<br /><span style="color: red"><span style="font-weight: bold">As for me</span></span>, <span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: blue">when it comes to apples</span></span>, &lt;I&gt; <span style="font-style: italic">like</span> &lt;those&gt;, but <span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: green">when it comes to Mr.Smith</span></span>, &lt;<span style="font-weight: bold">I</span>&gt; <span style="font-style: italic">don't like</span> &lt;<span style="font-weight: bold">him</span>&gt; <span style="font-style: italic">very much</span>.<br /><br />It you use ã instead, you are no longer contrasting ããã with other things:<br />ãç§<span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: red">ã¯</span></span>ããã<span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: blue">ã</span></span>å¥½ãã§ãããã¹ãã¹ãã<span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: green">ã¯</span></span>ãã¾ãå¥½ãã§ã¯ããã¾ããã<br /><span style="color: red"><span style="font-weight: bold">Personally speaking</span></span>, <span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: blue">apples</span></span> are what I like <span style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 116%;">(I like <span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: blue">apples</span></span>)</span>, but <span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="color: green">as for Mr.Smith</span></span>, &lt;<span style="font-weight: bold">he</span>&gt; <span style="font-style: italic">doesn't like</span> &lt;<span style="font-weight: bold">them</span>&gt; <span style="font-style: italic">very much</span>.<br /><br /><br />I hope this is all correct. -_-;<br />I wouldn't be surprised if it turned out one of those last two sentences could be read the other way...<br />(probably the first one.)<br /><br /><br />(Note that these are not intended as translations but explanations for understanding of ã¯ and ã. When translating these sentences, understand how the contrast is working, and translate appropriately without throwing a hundred &quot;as for&quot;s and &quot;when it comes to&quot;s all over the English.)<br /><br />Also note that there's probably a million topics already explaining ã¯ and ã which you might want to search for and have a read through if you're confused. ^^</div>

