			<h3 ><a href="#p160633">Re: To (probably) discuss a lot of basics</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="http://thejapanesepage.com/forum/viewtopic.php?p=160633&amp;sid=ccca31e45dd7a790da195e88f9dcfb63#p160633"><img src="http://thejapanesepage.com/phpbb/styles/tjp-embed/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="http://thejapanesepage.com/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=26732&amp;sid=ccca31e45dd7a790da195e88f9dcfb63">furrykef</a></strong> &raquo; Mon 11.09.2009 12:48 pm </p>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote><div><cite>Astral Abraxas wrote:</cite><blockquote><div><cite>furrykef wrote:</cite>But that doesn't explain why you wouldn't say ç§ã¯ãããã¯å¥½ãã§ã unless you wanted to contrast ããã with something like ã¿ãã.<br /></div></blockquote><br /><br />Actually yes it does furrykef.</div></blockquote><br /><br />This may seem a blunt question, but... what kind of response is that? If that's a valid argument, I could just respond in kind with &quot;no it doesn't&quot; and suddenly we're in <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kQFKtI6gn9Y" class="postlink">a Monty Python sketch</a>. <img src="http://thejapanesepage.com/phpbb/images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" /><br /><br />Let's analyze this logically, or try to, at least:<br />1. We have the sentence ç§ã¯ãããã¯å¥½ãã§ã, which sets up the sentence ã¿ããã¯å«ãã§ã.<br />2. If the first sentence were not designed to set up the second sentence, the speaker would have instead chosen to say, ç§ã¯ããã<span style="font-weight: bold">ã</span>å¥½ãã§ã.<br />3. Therefore, the entire purpose of using ã¯ after ããã is to contrast it with ã¿ãã.<br /><br />There you have it: ã¯ is a contrastive particle.<br /><br />Now, can you show me a similar thought process that demonstrates that ã¯ is a topical particle in this context?<br /><br />- Kef</div>

