		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p160650">Re: To (probably) discuss a lot of basics</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="http://thejapanesepage.com/forum/viewtopic.php?p=160650&amp;sid=ccca31e45dd7a790da195e88f9dcfb63#p160650"><img src="http://thejapanesepage.com/phpbb/styles/tjp-embed/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="http://thejapanesepage.com/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=22871&amp;sid=ccca31e45dd7a790da195e88f9dcfb63">Astral Abraxas</a></strong> &raquo; Mon 11.09.2009 4:52 pm </p>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote><div><cite>furrykef wrote:</cite>This may seem a blunt question, but... what kind of response is that? If that's a valid argument, I could just respond in kind with &quot;no it doesn't&quot; and suddenly we're in a Monty Python sketch. <img src="http://thejapanesepage.com/phpbb/images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" /><br /><br />Let's analyze this logically, or try to, at least:<br />1. We have the sentence ç§ã¯ãããã¯å¥½ãã§ã, which sets up the sentence ã¿ããã¯å«ãã§ã.<br />2. If the first sentence were not designed to set up the second sentence, the speaker would have instead chosen to say, ç§ã¯ããããå¥½ãã§ã.<br />3. Therefore, the entire purpose of using ã¯ after ããã is to contrast it with ã¿ãã.<br /><br />There you have it: ã¯ is a contrastive particle.<br /><br />Now, can you show me a similar thought process that demonstrates that ã¯ is a topical particle in this context?<br /></div></blockquote><br /><br />You honestly think I don't realize that my post was nearly useless? I wasn't trying to be informative. I was simply disagreeing.<br /><br />I have 1 question for you though. What do you think would happen if you put two topics next to each other? We almost always instinctively compare them without even realizing it <span style="font-weight: bold">if you're not tunnel-visioned on grammar</span>. If one is negative and one is positive then naturally it's going to contrast when we do that instinctive comparison.<br /><br />The problem is if you're not familiar with the language it's not obvious as to why they used ã¯ it's not obvious that it's contrasting even though it's very straight forward and quite logical. It's not really so much an exception or rule as it is common sense IN MY OPINION.<br /><br />If I say:<br /><br />I like apples. I don't like oranges.<br /><br />You'll compare them without even realizing it. This is about learning how Japanese take advantage of the fact ã¯ marks the topic. The things you're labeling as exceptions aren't exceptions. They are things that can be deduced with a little thinking and an understanding that the particle ã¯ marks the topic. They're just something you most likely can't come up with on your own if you're new to the language.<br /><br />It's pretty straight forward.<br /><br />Simply put:<br /><br />You're suppose to be comparing two topics instinctively but since you're not Japanese it's not so instinctive.<br />Due to the fact one is positive and one is negative that comparison results in a contrast.</div>

			

		</div>

		
			<dl class="postprofile" id="profile160650">
			<dt>
				<a href="http://thejapanesepage.com/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=22871&amp;sid=ccca31e45dd7a790da195e88f9dcfb63"><img src="http://thejapanesepage.com/phpbb/download/file.php?avatar=22871_1256452088.jpg" width="81" height="98" alt="User avatar" /></a><br />
