			<div class="content"><blockquote><div><cite>furrykef wrote:</cite>Well, I think this goes back to my &quot;two sides of the same coin&quot; point. Perhaps topicality and contrast aren't actually different things.<br /><br />- Kef</div></blockquote><br /><br />Well that's thing. Topics are contrastive by nature.<br />As soon as you make something a topic, for instance,ãç§ã¯, you are in a away saying contrasting yourself to everything else. It's I, not you, he, Miyazaki, or anyone else.<br /><br />But then again, I don't really mind if people think of a topic ã¯ and a contrastive ã¯, if that makes it easier to learn.<br />But linguistically speaking, there is only one ã¯ in the Japanese language.</div>

